  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The invocation sequence of services is shown for each process or sub-process in a sequence diagram describing the&#xD;
    interaction between the services involved. It will be an orchestration of services if there is an&amp;nbsp;organization&#xD;
    that controls its, or a choreography if it involves more than one organization in a collaborative process with&#xD;
    pre-defined communication with other parties.&lt;span&#xD;
    style=&quot;FONT-FAMILY: 'Times','serif'; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-bidi-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: DE; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;&#xD;
     lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;>This insight is provided by a sequence diagram showing all the services, or various sequence diagrams&#xD;
    showing different subsets of services corresponding to different sub-processes in the business&#xD;
    process.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span>&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Example of a sequence diagram showing an interaction of services for the sub-process &quot;Loan Authorization&quot; from a &quot;Grant&#xD;
    Loan&quot; business process of a bank:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;resources/sequencediagram.jpg&quot; width=&quot;600&quot; height=&quot;572&quot; />&lt;br />&#xD;
    &amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
